Throughout inland Bolivia, there is still a vivid memory of the coastline that the country lost in favor of Chile in the bloody war for resources in the 19th century – as well as the desire to resurrect the Pacific Ocean.
These aspirations are perhaps the biggest in decades, as Bolivia awaits a ruling by the international court of justice, which is due to expire on October 1 after five years of negotiations.
"Bolivia has energy, a spirit of unity and calm, and of course expects a positive result," said Bolivian diplomat Roberto Calzadilla.
Many Bolivians will be watching the MSD’s decisions on big screens across the country in the hope that a tribunal in The Hague will rule in favor of Bolivia’s claim that – after many decades of intermittent talks – Chile is obliged to negotiate giving Bolivia sovereign access to the sea.
Bolivia’s charismatic indigenous president, Evo Morales — who faces a controversial battle for re-election next year — also has a keen interest in Monday’s decision.
"We are very close to returning to the Pacific Ocean," he said at the end of August.
But some analysts believe it is unlikely that a court would rule in Bolivia’s favor — and even if it did, not much would change.
The Netherlands-based UN body has no power to assign territory to anyone in Chile and said it would not determine the outcome of possible talks.
The fact that the MSD’s decision comes just six months after the last arguments were made shows that the case “wasn’t complicated,” according to Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law.
