He adds that Morales’ offensive rhetoric has weakened all remaining goodwill in Chile.
Bolivia and Chile will one day begin to act again, but after that it will be extremely difficult to hold discussions.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodr<0xC3><0xAD>guez Veltzé, Bolivia's representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the court's decision was unusually swift.
Monday will bring Bolivia "an exceptional opportunity to usher in a new era of relations with Chile" and a chance "to end 139 years of disagreements with mutual benefits," he said.
Calzadilla also refused that Morales – still one of the most popular presidents in Latin America – would use the question of the sea as a political crutch.
