John Edward: Language skills are a necessity for global citizens
Scottish independent schools have had a number of academic successes, and this continues in 2018 with other excellent exam results. Individual and group successes in sports, art, music and other community activities only underline this.
These schools have more than 30,000 pupils across Scotland, are represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) and strive to provide the best possible level of service to their pupils and parents.
Independent schools prepare their students for further and higher education, the career they have chosen, and their place as global citizens.
As a sector of education that can design and implement individually tailored school education plans, we observe that modern languages are still a popular and sought-after subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to a person in a language they understand, it goes straight to their head.
If you talk to him in his own language, it goes straight to his heart.”
It is a significant observation that if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries, we cannot rely only on English.
The latest results of this year's exams show that languages are in the first place of the tables, with independent schools having the highest success rate.
A total of 68 percent of pupils who learned a foreign language achieved the best grade of A.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools show that 72% of Mandarin students, 72% of German students, 69% of French students and 63% of Spanish students achieved the highest A grade.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as important skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages as the subjects that students choose are equally valued in the curricula of independent and other schools as STEM subjects (science, technology, technical fields and mathematics).
A survey conducted by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 showed that 17 per cent of the reasons employers cite as problems in filling vacancies are insufficient language skills.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly becoming a necessity in preparing young people for their future careers.
As more and more jobs require languages, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Whichever career you choose, if you have learned a second language, you will have the real advantage of having such a lifelong skill in the future.
Thanks to the ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries, a person who speaks multiple languages will automatically gain an advantage over the competition.
According to a survey conducted by YouGov in 2013 among 4,000 adults in the UK, 75 per cent of them were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to lead a conversation, with the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage of people, namely 15 per cent, being French.
Therefore, it is important for today’s children to invest in language teaching.
If children know more languages, especially the languages of emerging economies, they will be more likely to find meaningful employment.
In Scotland, every school differs in what languages it teaches.
Many schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others teach the languages considered most important to the UK in the 2020 outlook, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
No matter what the child is interested in, he will always have a choice of several languages at independent schools with teachers who are experts in the field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing an educational environment that prepares and equips children with the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future holds for them.
At the moment, there is no denying that languages are essential for the future of the country in the global business environment, so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should actually be considered “international communication skills.”
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and prominence to young people in Scotland.
I'll be honest with you.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
