North Korea says it will not “under any circumstances” arm itself unilaterally and without confidence
North Korea’s foreign minister said on Saturday that continued UN sanctions had deepened its distrust of the United States and under such circumstances the country would never give up its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho said at his annual general assembly that North Korea had taken “significant goodwill measures” over the past year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the site of nuclear tests and promising not to spread nuclear weapons and technology.
"But we do not see a corresponding response from the United States," he said.
“Without confidence in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security, and it is not possible to disarm unilaterally under such circumstances.”
While Ri echoed well-known North Korean complaints about Washington’s opposition to a “gradual” approach to denuclearization, under which North Korea would be rewarded for each step it took, his statement seemed significant in that it did not reject unilateral denuclearization just because Pyongyang had gone through it in the past.
Ri mentioned a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between the U.S. president and North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work for the “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula,” while Trump pledged security guarantees for North Korea.
North Korea is seeking a formal end to the 1950-53 war, but the United States has said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease tough international sanctions against North Korea.
“The U.S. insists on ‘denuclearization first’ and increases pressure on sanctions to enforce its targets, and even objects to ‘declaring an end to the war,’” Ri said.
“The idea that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a dream of people who know nothing about us.
But the problem is that continued sanctions are deepening our mistrust.”
Ri made no mention of plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the U.S. leader stressed at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If South Korea and not the US were on the side of this issue of denuclearization, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have come to such a stalemate.”
However, the tone of Ri’s speech was dramatically different from last year when he told the U.N. General Assembly that targeting North Korea’s missiles on U.S. soil was inevitable after “Mr. Bad President” Trump labeled Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
At the United Nations this year, Trump, who last year threatened the “total destruction” of North Korea, praised Kim for his courage to take steps to disarm, but said much work remains to be done and sanctions must remain in place until North Korea is fully denuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no time frame for it, saying, “If it takes two years, three years, or five months — it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia say the U.N. Security Council should reward Pyongyang for taking action.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that “the enforcement of Security Council sanctions must continue vigorously and relentlessly until we realize complete, final, verified denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously supported sanctions against North Korea since 2006 in an effort to curb funding for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo and Ri met at the U.N. General Assembly, and Pompeo said he would visit Pyongyang next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times so far this year, but his latest trip did not end well.
