Harvard students participate in a course designed to teach them enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has prompted all of its students to sleep more, in an effort to combat the growing culture of macho study all night long when students are awake and encouraged with caffeine.
Academics have found that students at the world’s most renowned university are often clueless when it comes to the basics of self-care.
The course was designed by Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham Hospital and Women’s Hospital, which he believes is the first of its kind in the US.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a lecture on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At the end, a girl came to me and said, ‘Why are you only telling me this now, in my senior year?’
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep — which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was first introduced this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance and improve their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university had decided to introduce the course after finding that students were seriously sleep-deprived during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one part, there is an image of student dorms where students click on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers and books about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by lack of sleep and the importance of proper sleep habits.
In another section, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
The campus map with interactive icons then encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
“We know that the behavior of students will not change immediately.
However, we believe they have a right to know - just as you have a right to know the health effects of smoking cigarettes," Professor Czeisler added.
A culture of pride in “all-night studying” still exists, he added, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students mean that the problem of lack of sleep is also growing.
Getting enough good quality sleep should be a student’s “secret weapon” to combat stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, he said — even to keep from gaining weight, because sleep deprivation switches the brain into starvation mode so that the person is still hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student of chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design a course that one of his classes took last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to push the whole course.
He hopes that the next step will be to ask all graduate students to complete a similar degree program before entering a competitive institution.
The professor recommended that students consider setting an alarm for when to go to bed, as well as when to wake up, and be aware of the harmful effects of the “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting that can disrupt your circadian rhythm, leading to trouble falling asleep.
