Red tide update: Concentrations decrease in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota districts
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission points to an overall decline in red tide concentrations in the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, spots of blooming water are now reported from the districts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier – this indicates a decreasing concentration.
The flowering water of the red tide has a range of about 130 miles of coastline from the northern district of Pinellas to the southern district of Lee.
Spots were observed about 10 miles off the coast in Hillsborough County, but last week it was relatively fewer places.
A red tide was also observed in the Pasco district.
In Hillsborough County, low to high concentrations, low to high concentrations, in Manatee County, low to high concentrations, in Sarasota County, low to medium concentrations, and in Charlotte County, low to high concentrations, or in the coastal or high concentrations, have been observed in the high seas.
Respiratory irritations continue to occur in the districts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
Airway irritation was not reported in northwest Florida last week.
